01. matplotlib Package¶

  • comprehensive library for creating static, animated, and interactive visualizations in Python
  • multi-platform data visualisation library built on NumPy arrays
  • forms basis of many other popular Python plotting packages

Further Reading:

  • https://matplotlib.org/index.html

how to import? alias?¶

In [2]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

Further Reading:

  • https://matplotlib.org/stable/api/_as_gen/matplotlib.pyplot.html?highlight=pyplot#module-matplotlib.pyplot

02. Anatomy of a Figure: Figures vs Axes¶

Figure = the whole figure

  • axes
    • 2D vs 3D
  • canvas
    • where everything is drawn
  • artists
    • anything drawn on the canvas
  • axes
    • 2D vs 3D
      • data is plotted within Axes
    • labels of the x and y axes
    • tick spacing
    • legends
    • etc
  • canvas
    • where everything is drawn
    • i.e. upon which plots shown, one or more plots
      • may contain several axes
    • effectively invisible by user
  • artists
    • anything drawn on the canvas
      • titles,
      • figure legends,
      • colour of the background,
      • etc
      • even the Figure, Axes, and Axis objects

Further Reading:

  • https://matplotlib.org/faq/usage_faq.html#usage
  • artists
    • https://matplotlib.org/api/artist_api.html
    • https://matplotlib.org/tutorials/intermediate/artists.html

03. API modes¶

  • two approaches to plotting with Matplotlib

    • Object Oriented API (follows the Python object model)

    • MATLAB-like API (aka pyplot API)

Further Reading:

  • https://matplotlib.org/api/index.html
  • https://matplotlib.org/tutorials/introductory/lifecycle.html

04. Object Oriented API¶

  1. Create a Figure object
  • Using a figure method to create one or more Axes (within the Figure object)
  • Using the axes object method create one or more plots within (for each axes)

from numpy import sqrt
from numpy import meshgrid
from numpy import arange

xs = arange(-7.25, 7.25, 0.01)
ys = arange(-5, 5, 0.01)
x, y = meshgrid(xs, ys)

eq1 = ((x/7)**2*sqrt(abs(abs(x)-3)/(abs(x)-3))+(y/3)**2*sqrt(abs(y+3/7*sqrt(33))/(y+3/7*sqrt(33)))-1)
eq2 = (abs(x/2)-((3*sqrt(33)-7)/112)*x**2-3+sqrt(1-(abs(abs(x)-2)-1)**2)-y)
eq3 = (9*sqrt(abs((abs(x)-1)*(abs(x)-.75))/((1-abs(x))*(abs(x)-.75)))-8*abs(x)-y)
eq4 = (3*abs(x)+.75*sqrt(abs((abs(x)-.75)*(abs(x)-.5))/((.75-abs(x))*(abs(x)-.5)))-y)
eq5 = (2.25*sqrt(abs((x-.5)*(x+.5))/((.5-x)*(.5+x)))-y)
eq6 = (6*sqrt(10)/7+(1.5-.5*abs(x))*sqrt(abs(abs(x)-1)/(abs(x)-1))-(6*sqrt(10)/14)*sqrt(4-(abs(x)-1)**2)-y)

can we add some colour to the plot?¶
ax.scatter(x, y, marker = '*', s = df_resp['Weight'], 

           # colour arguement
           c = df_resp['Gender']
          )

causes a ValueError due to string

how to avoid?

  • mpl color, or a sequence of mpl colors, or
  • a sequence of numbers
In [39]:
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(15,5))

ax = fig.add_subplot(1,1,1, title = 'survey data')
ax.scatter(x, y, marker = '*', s = df_resp['Weight'], 

           # colour
           c = pd.Series([0, 1]).repeat(len(df_resp)/2))

ax.set_xlabel('Weight'); ax.set_ylabel('Height'); ax.set_xticks(np.arange(20, 150 + 1, 5)); ax.set_yticks(np.arange(55, 220 + 1, 15)) ; ax.set_xlim(40, 130, 5); ax.set_ylim(130, 220, 15);

fig = plt.figure(figsize=(15,5))

          )
